Phase 0 – Mindset + Setup (First 30–60 Days – Start Right Now)

1. Simple & Strong Mindset  
You are early — enjoy the advantage, don’t slow down for batch  
Daily small work is better than big weekend study marathons  
College marks matter — keep CGPA 7.5+ (don’t drop below 7.0)  
Mistakes are normal — learn from them, don’t fear them  
Balance is key: code + friends + rest + college + family time  
One good DSA problem + one project step + one internship application = real win  

2. Easy & Useful Tracking  
Use one Google Sheet, Notion page, or even notebook.  
Every week write these things (takes 5–10 min):  
- Week number  
- How many DSA problems solved this week (medium/hard count)  
- What project work I did (feature added, bug fixed, deployed?)  
- Did I apply for any internship? (yes/no + where)  
- One good thing I did this week  
- Energy level (1–10) or how I feel  

Every Sunday spend 10–15 min:  
- See what you did last week  
- Plan next 7 days (example: “finish Titanic model + 10 medium problems”)  
- Re-solve 4–6 problems you found hard  

This simple tracking keeps you motivated without stress.

3. Online Presence – Low Effort, High Result  
LinkedIn (start building now — recruiters look early)  
- Headline: B.Tech CSE AIML '29 | Python + ML | 400+ DSA | Looking for AI Internships  
- About section: 4–6 lines — write something like:  
  “First-year CSE AIML student passionate about AI and Machine Learning. Solved 300+ DSA problems, built several ML projects (links below). Learning daily and open to internships early.”  
- Skills to add: Python, Machine Learning, Data Analysis, Numpy, Pandas, Git, Scikit-learn  
- Post 1 time per week: simple project screenshot, one problem you solved, small progress update  

GitHub (your online resume)  
- Bio: First-Year CSE AIML • Python & ML • Building AI Projects  
- Pin 5–8 best repositories  
- Every repo should have:  
  - Project name and one-line description  
  - Tech used (Python, libraries)  
  - How to run (simple steps)  
  - Screenshots or GIF demo  
  - Live link if deployed  

4. Daily Routine – College-Friendly & Balanced  
Normal College Days (1.5–3 hours total)  
- 40–60 minutes DSA practice (1–2 medium problems + revision)  
- 40–60 minutes project or ML coding  
- 20–30 minutes watch video / read notes  
- 10 minutes apply to internship or post on LinkedIn  

Free Days / Weekends (4–5 hours total)  
- 1.5 hours DSA (3–4 medium problems or 1–2 hard)  
- 1.5 hours project building or ML model training  
- 45 minutes core subject revision or Kaggle notebook  
- 30 minutes rest, application, or fun  

No zero days rule — even 30–45 minutes counts a lot (watch short video + solve one problem).  
If exam time — reduce to 30–60 min/day — that’s fine.

5. Health & Balance – Very Important in First Year  
- Sleep minimum 7 hours — brain needs rest to learn  
- Walk, play sports, or exercise 20–40 minutes daily  
- One lighter day per week (only revision + relax)  
- Eat normal food — avoid junk every day  
- Talk to friends/family — don’t sit alone coding all time  
- If feeling tired — take break, watch movie, sleep extra  

Phase 1 – DSA + Python + ML Basics (Months 1–6 of Second Year)

1. DSA – Strengthen Medium Level  
Focus: Mostly medium problems + some hard (quality much more important than quantity)  

Monthly Topics (easy pace)  
Months 1–2  
- Advanced arrays/lists: Kadane algorithm, two pointers technique, sliding window problems  
- Strings: anagram check, longest palindrome substring, string compression  
- Binary search: more problems (rotated array, find peak, kth smallest)  

Months 3–4  
- Linked list: reverse list, detect cycle, find middle, remove nth node  
- Stack & Queue: next greater element, valid parentheses, min stack  
- Recursion: subsets, permutations (easy-medium), combination sum  

Months 5–6  
- Trees basics: binary tree traversal (pre/in/post/level), height, diameter intro  
- Graphs intro: BFS/DFS on grid, number of islands basics  
- Greedy easy-medium: jump game, activity selection  

Target by End Second Year: 600–900 total problems  
- 400–600 medium  
- 80–150 hard (only if you enjoy them)  

Resources (pick 2–3)  
- Striver SDE Sheet (medium focus)  
- Love Babbar 450  
- takeUforward YouTube  
- LeetCode explore cards  

Rule: Think 15–30 min → hint → try → solution. Write clean code + note time/space + pattern.

2. Python for AI/ML – Get Really Good  
- Numpy: arrays, broadcasting, math operations, vectorization  
- Pandas: read CSV/Excel, clean data, groupby, merge, pivot tables  
- Matplotlib/Seaborn: line plots, bar charts, histograms, heatmaps  
- Scikit-learn basics: train_test_split, scaling, metrics, simple models  

Resources  
- Kaggle Python & Pandas course (free, interactive)  
- CampusX YouTube (Hindi, very clear)  
- freeCodeCamp Data Analysis with Python  
- Pandas documentation quick examples  

Practice:  
- Load any CSV from Kaggle  
- Clean missing values  
- Make 5–10 plots  
- Do simple groupby analysis  

3. ML Basics – Hands-On & Fun  
Topics (easy to understand)  
- Supervised vs unsupervised learning  
- Regression: linear, polynomial, evaluation (MSE, R²)  
- Classification: logistic, decision tree, random forest, evaluation (accuracy, confusion matrix)  
- Metrics: precision, recall, F1-score, ROC curve intro  
- Overfitting/underfitting: how to spot & fix  
- Cross-validation: k-fold basics  

Projects (Do 5–8 – these are resume gold)  
1. House price prediction (Boston or simple Kaggle dataset)  
2. Titanic survival prediction (classic Kaggle)  
3. Iris flower classification (easy & beautiful)  
4. Breast cancer prediction (Wisconsin dataset)  
5. Diabetes prediction (Pima Indians dataset)  
6. Customer churn prediction (telecom dataset)  
7. Wine quality prediction (regression/classification)  
8. Heart disease prediction  

Platforms  
- Kaggle notebooks (free, GPU available)  
- Google Colab (free)  

Goal for each project:  
- Load data  
- Clean & explore  
- Train 2–3 models  
- Compare results  
- Make notebook nice  
- Deploy simple app (Streamlit)  

